{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter X: Costing Methodologies\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter X delves into various costing methodologies, focusing primarily on Activity-Based Costing (ABC) and Absorption Costing. The chapter aims to provide a comprehensive understanding of how these costing methods are applied in both service and manufacturing industries. Key concepts include the identification and use of cost drivers, the allocation of overhead costs, and the comparison between traditional absorption costing and ABC. The chapter also includes practical examples and quizzes to test the application of these methodologies in real-world scenarios. By the end of the chapter, students should be able to differentiate between these costing methods, understand their applications, and evaluate their effectiveness in different contexts.\",\n    \"rating\": 8.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The chapter is highly significant due to its detailed exploration of fundamental costing methodologies essential for accurate financial management and decision-making.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Activity-Based Costing (ABC) provides more accurate cost information by focusing on activities and cost drivers.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Activity-Based Costing (ABC) is a costing methodology that assigns costs to activities based on their use of resources, applicable in both service and manufacturing industries. This approach provides more accurate cost information by linking costs to specific activities and focusing on the activities that incur costs. ABC involves tracing resource consumption and costing final outputs by identifying cost drivers, which are used to attach activity costs to outputs. Overhead and indirect costs are assigned to related products and services through this method, ensuring a detailed and precise allocation of costs [Data: Concepts (133, 1575); Relationships (118, 109, 121, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Absorption costing includes all manufacturing costs in the unit cost of a product or service.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Absorption costing is a traditional costing method that involves calculating the unit cost of a product or service by including all manufacturing costs. This includes direct materials, direct labor, and both variable and fixed manufacturing overheads. The process involves several steps: allocation and apportionment of costs to cost centers, re-apportionment of service center costs to production cost centers, and absorption of the total cost into the unit cost using an appropriate basis. Typically, a single overhead rate is used to allocate costs based on a common measure such as direct labor hours or machine hours [Data: Concepts (176, 134); Relationships (132, 110, 137, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Cost drivers are essential in ABC for allocating costs to activities.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"A cost driver is a factor that can cause a change in the cost of an activity. In ABC, cost drivers are used to apportion overhead costs to products based on the use of activities by each product. This methodology involves identifying the activities within an organization and assigning the cost of each activity to all products and services based on their actual consumption. By doing so, ABC helps in more accurately tracing costs to products and services [Data: Concepts (135, 1575); Relationships (118, 109, 121, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Quizzes in the chapter test the application and understanding of ABC in various contexts.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes several quizzes designed to test the application and understanding of Activity-Based Costing (ABC) in different contexts. For instance, the 'ABC in Manufacturing Quiz' tests knowledge on the application and judgment required in ABC in a manufacturing environment, while the 'ABC in Service Industries Quiz' focuses on the relevance and principles of ABC in service industries. Other quizzes involve calculating budgeted overhead costs, fixed overhead costs, and comparing ABC with traditional costing systems [Data: Concepts (1239, 1238, 1241, 1242, +more); Relationships (124, 125, 126, 127, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Case studies illustrate the practical application of ABC and its impact on pricing strategies.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes case studies that illustrate the practical application of Activity-Based Costing (ABC) and its impact on pricing strategies. For example, the case of Beckley Hill Hospital evaluates the implementation of ABC to more accurately price its procedures, while the case of Brick By Brick (BBB) discusses how ABC can address issues with overhead absorption and improve pricing competitiveness. These case studies provide real-world examples of how ABC can be used to enhance financial management and decision-making [Data: Concepts (1582, 1574); Relationships (131, 1490, 1493, 1494, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Traditional absorption costing may not accurately reflect true product overhead costs in modern factories.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Traditional absorption costing is a method where overhead costs are allocated to products based on a single cost driver, such as labor hours or machine hours. This method typically uses direct labor hours or machine hours to apportion all overhead costs between products. However, this method may not accurately reflect the true product overhead costs, especially in modern factories with significant overhead costs. For instance, in the case of the Deluxe model, the overhead cost would be only 20% more than that of a Basic model, which may not be accurate [Data: Concepts (134, 133); Relationships (110, 137, 133, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Fixed production overheads are included in the unit cost in absorption costing.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Fixed production overheads are costs that do not vary with the level of production and are included in the unit cost in absorption costing. These overheads encompass indirect costs of production, such as rent, salaries, depreciation, and utilities. They are typically associated with expenses that remain constant regardless of the output level, including the salaries of permanent staff. Absorption costing involves calculating these fixed overheads and including them in the unit cost of a product or service [Data: Concepts (188, 176); Relationships (175, 179, 233, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Marginal costing considers only variable costs in the unit cost of a product or service.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Marginal costing involves calculating the unit cost of a product or service by considering only variable costs. Fixed costs are treated as period costs and are not included in the unit cost. This method is useful for decision-making processes where the focus is on the contribution margin, which is the difference between sales revenue and variable costs. Marginal costing helps in understanding the impact of variable costs on the overall profitability of a product or service [Data: Concepts (177, 183); Relationships (173, 182, 184, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Environmental Management Accounting (EMA) uses ABC to manage environmental costs effectively.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Environmental Management Accounting (EMA) uses Activity-Based Costing (ABC) to manage environmental costs more effectively by identifying cost drivers and reducing their use without reducing output. This approach helps organizations to better understand the environmental impact of their activities and to allocate costs more accurately. By using ABC, EMA can provide more detailed and meaningful information for decision-making processes related to environmental management [Data: Concepts (1316); Relationships (122, 1316)].\"\n        }\n    ]\n}", "input": "\nYou are an AI assistant that helps a human analyst to perform general information discovery within a textbook. Information discovery is the process of identifying and assessing relevant information associated with certain entities (e.g., concepts, methodologies, quizzes, examples, cases) within a chapter of a textbook.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive report of a chapter, given a list of concepts, methodologies, formulas and examples that belong to the chapter as well as their relationships and optional associated claims. The report will be used to inform educators and students about the chapter's content and its key components. The content of this report includes an overview of the chapter's key entities, their definitions, interrelations, and noteworthy details.\n\n# Report Structure\n\nThe report should include the following sections:\n\n- TITLE: Chapter title - the title is given in the textbook in the format 'Chapter X: title'\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary that outlines the chapter's structure and the main learning outcomes. Focus on the key concepts as mentioned in the learning outcomes, their relevant examples, formulas, and methodologies, and how these elements are related to each other.\n- IMPACT SEVERITY RATING: a float score between 0-10 that represents the significance of the chapter's content. This score reflects the importance and relevance of the chapter's material in the context of the textbook.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the significance rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the chapter. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format:\n    {{\n        \"title\": <report_title>,\n        \"summary\": <executive_summary>,\n        \"rating\": <impact_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": <rating_explanation>,\n        \"findings\": [\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_1_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_1_explanation>\n            }},\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_2_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_2_explanation>\n            }}\n        ]\n    }}\n\n# Grounding Rules\n\nPoints supported by data should list their data references as follows:\n\n\"This is an example sentence supported by multiple data references [Data: <dataset name> (record ids); <dataset name> (record ids)].\"\n\nDo not list more than 5 record ids in a single reference. Instead, list the top 5 most relevant record ids and add \"+more\" to indicate that there are more.\n\nFor example:\n\"The concept of Expected Value is fundamental to Chapter 8 and is illustrated through multiple examples [Data: Concepts (5, 7, 12); Examples (3, 8, 15, +more)].\"\n\nwhere 5, 7, 12, 3, 8, and 15 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n1,FOCUS GROUP,Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n133,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"Activity-Based Costing (ABC) is a costing methodology that assigns costs to activities based on their use of resources, applicable in both service and manufacturing industries. This approach provides more accurate cost information by linking costs to specific activities and focusing on the activities that incur costs. ABC involves tracing resource consumption and costing final outputs by identifying cost drivers, which are used to attach activity costs to outputs. Overhead and indirect costs are assigned to related products and services through this method, ensuring a detailed and precise allocation of costs.\",24\n176,\"\"\"ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"Absorption costing is a traditional costing method that involves calculating the unit cost of a product or service by including all manufacturing costs. This includes direct materials, direct labor, and both variable and fixed manufacturing overheads. The process involves several steps: allocation and apportionment of costs to cost centers, re-apportionment of service center costs to production cost centers, and absorption of the total cost into the unit cost using an appropriate basis. Typically, a single overhead rate is used to allocate costs based on a common measure such as direct labor hours or machine hours.\",10\n134,\"\"\"TRADITIONAL ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"Traditional absorption costing is a method where overhead costs are allocated to products based on a single cost driver, such as labor hours or machine hours. This method typically uses direct labor hours or machine hours to apportion all overhead costs between products. For instance, in the case of the Deluxe model, the overhead cost would be only 20% more than that of a Basic model. However, this method may not accurately reflect the true product overhead costs, especially in modern factories with significant overhead costs.\",7\n175,\"\"\"MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Management accounting is concerned with preparing and presenting accounting information to assist management in planning, controlling, and making decisions.\"\"\",3\n1582,\"\"\"EVALUATING COSTING METHODS FOR ACCURATE PROCEDURE PRICING AT BECKLEY HILL HOSPITAL\"\"\",\"\"\"Beckley Hill (BH) is a private hospital evaluating the implementation of activity-based costing (ABC) to more accurately price its procedures. The hospital currently uses a simple overhead allocation method but is considering ABC to better reflect the costs associated with different activities such as administrative time, nursing, catering, and general facility costs.\"\"\",2\n1239,\"\"\"ABC IN MANUFACTURING QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"A quiz that tests knowledge on the application and judgment required in activity-based costing in a manufacturing environment.\"\"\",1\n1238,\"\"\"ABC IN SERVICE INDUSTRIES QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"A quiz that tests knowledge on the relevance and principles of activity-based costing in service industries.\"\"\",1\n186,\"\"\"ABSORPTION RATES\"\"\",\"\"\"Absorption rates are calculated in ABC to determine the overhead costs per unit of activity.\"\"\",1\n185,\"\"\"ACTIVITY COST POOLS\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity cost pools are groups of individual costs that are associated with a specific activity in ABC.\"\"\",1\n170,\"\"\"ACTIVITY OF ANAESTHETIST\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity of anaesthetist is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by the number of operations, calculated separately for those requiring a general anaesthetic and those requiring only local anaesthetics.\"\"\",1\n172,\"\"\"ACTIVITY OF THE PHYSICIAN\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity of the physician is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by the time taken from initial incision to closure of incision on completion of surgery.\"\"\",1\n135,\"\"\"COST DRIVER\"\"\",\"\"\"A cost driver is a factor that can cause a change in the cost of an activity. In ABC, cost drivers are used to apportion overhead costs to products based on the use of activities by each product.\"\"\",1\n169,\"\"\"PREPARING THE OPERATING THEATRE\"\"\",\"\"\"Preparing the operating theatre is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by the number of operations. The cost does not vary significantly between different types of operations.\"\"\",1\n171,\"\"\"ANAESTHETIC DRUGS\"\"\",\"\"\"Anaesthetic drugs is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by the time taken from entering the anaesthetic room until entering the recovery room.\"\"\",1\n173,\"\"\"CONSUMABLE ITEMS DURING SURGERY\"\"\",\"\"\"Consumable items during surgery is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by an itemised list of consumables used during surgery, captured by a bar-coding device.\"\"\",1\n174,\"\"\"OVERHEAD ACTIVITY\"\"\",\"\"\"Overhead activity is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by a charge for management administration and staff training.\"\"\",1\n1241,\"\"\"QUIZ: BUDGETED OVERHEAD COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the budgeted overhead cost per unit of the product 'Me' using activity-based costing. It provides information on production set-up costs, ordering costs, and other overhead costs, and requires the calculation of overhead costs per unit.\"\"\",1\n1242,\"\"\"QUIZ: FIXED OVERHEAD COSTS IN ABC\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the budgeted fixed overhead cost per unit of product 'Ed' using activity-based costing. It provides information on material costs, labor costs, machine hours, and fixed overheads, and requires the calculation of fixed overhead costs per unit.\"\"\",1\n1243,\"\"\"QUIZ: ADVANTAGES OF ABC\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves identifying the advantages of using activity-based costing (ABC). It provides statements about ABC and requires selecting the correct advantages.\"\"\",1\n1244,\"\"\"QUIZ: THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION RANKING\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves ranking products based on their throughput contribution to maximize production efficiency. It provides information on selling price, material cost, variable costs, and time taken in the dyeing process for three products.\"\"\",1\n1338,\"\"\"QUIZ: OVERHEAD COST PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the budgeted overhead cost per unit of a product using activity-based costing (ABC). It provides information on production runs, inspections, and other overhead costs.\"\"\",1\n1339,\"\"\"QUIZ: ABC AND TRADITIONAL COSTING SYSTEMS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz compares activity-based costing (ABC) with traditional costing systems like absorption costing and marginal costing, focusing on their differences and applications.\"\"\",1\n188,\"\"\"FIXED PRODUCTION OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"Fixed production overheads are costs that do not vary with the level of production and are included in the unit cost in absorption costing. These overheads encompass indirect costs of production, such as rent, salaries, depreciation, and utilities. They are typically associated with expenses that remain constant regardless of the output level, including the salaries of permanent staff.\",3\n1575,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\"\"\",\"Activity-based costing (ABC) is a costing method that assigns overhead and indirect costs to related products and services by identifying cost drivers. This methodology involves identifying the activities within an organization and assigning the cost of each activity to all products and services based on their actual consumption. By doing so, ABC helps in more accurately tracing costs to products and services. The method allocates overheads to products based on activities that drive costs, such as machine setups, machine running, procurement, and delivery.\",9\n2228,\"\"\"SALES PRICE AND QUANTITY VARIANCES ANALYSIS FOR BLOCK CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Block Co uses an absorption costing system and sells three types of products. The company faces challenges in maintaining revenues and profits due to economic recession. Sales prices fluctuate, and a market specialist sets budgeted sales prices each quarter. The sales manager negotiates actual sales prices with customers.\"\"\",5\n1574,\"\"\"EVALUATING THE IMPACT OF ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING ON PRICING STRATEGIES AT BBB\"\"\",\"\"\"Brick By Brick (BBB) provides a range of building services, including garage conversions (GC) and extensions to properties (EX). BBB has a policy to price all jobs at budgeted total cost plus 50%. Overheads are currently absorbed on a labour hour basis. However, BBB has found that it has fewer GC contracts than expected, and it believes that this is because the current overhead absorption method apportions an excessive amount of overheads to GC, leading to a price that is uncompetitive. The company is now considering moving to an activity-based cost approach.\"\"\",6\n177,\"\"\"MARGINAL COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Marginal costing involves calculating the unit cost of a product or service by considering only variable costs. Fixed costs are treated as period costs and are not included in the unit cost.\"\"\",4\n182,\"\"\"TRADITIONAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Traditional management accounting is inward-looking, focusing on controlling costs. The most important techniques include costing systems (marginal and absorption costing), budgeting systems, standard costing and variance analysis, and working capital management.\"\"\",2\n939,\"\"\"MATERIALS VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"Materials variances are calculated to determine the difference between actual materials costs and standard materials costs. It includes materials price variance and materials usage variance.\"\"\",1\n940,\"\"\"LABOUR VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour variances are calculated to determine the difference between actual labor costs and standard labor costs. It includes labor rate variance, idle time variance, and labor efficiency variance.\"\"\",1\n941,\"\"\"VARIABLE OVERHEAD VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"Variable overhead variances are calculated to determine the difference between actual variable overhead costs and standard variable overhead costs. It includes variable overhead rate variance and variable overhead efficiency variance.\"\"\",1\n942,\"\"\"FIXED OVERHEAD VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed overhead variances are calculated to determine the difference between actual fixed overhead costs and budgeted fixed overhead costs. It includes fixed overhead expenditure variance.\"\"\",1\n1576,\"\"\"CURRENT METHOD OF ABSORBING OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"The current method of absorbing overheads at BBB is based on labour hours.\"\"\",2\n1577,\"\"\"SALES PRICE FOR A TYPICAL GC USING CURRENT METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"Price per unit using absorption cost plus 50%: Materials: $3,500, Labour (300 * 15): $4,500, Overheads (300 * ($400,000/40,000)): $3,000, Total cost: $11,000, Plus mark-up (50%): $5,500, Current price: $16,500.\"\"\",2\n1578,\"\"\"COST OF A GC USING ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Cost per unit using activity-based costing: Materials: $3,500, Labour (300 * 15): $4,500, Overheads: Supervisors (1 * 180): $180, Planners (1 * 280): $280, Property related (300 * 6): $1,800, Total cost: $10,260.\"\"\",2\n1579,\"\"\"COST PER UNIT OF A TYPICAL EX USING ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Cost per unit of a typical EX using activity-based costing: Materials: $8,000, Labour (500 * 15): $7,500, Overheads: Supervisors (6 * 180): $1,080, Planners (5 * 280): $1,400, Property related (500 * 6): $3,000, Total cost: $20,980, Therefore quoted price at 50% mark-up (20,980 * 150%): $31,470.\"\"\",2\n1580,\"\"\"QUIZ ON ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING AT BBB\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz involves questions about the sales price for a typical GC using the current method of absorbing overheads, the cost of a GC using activity-based costing, the cost per unit of a typical EX using activity-based costing, and statements about the usefulness of activity-based costing and environmental activity-based costing.\"\"\",2\n2044,\"\"\"COST ANALYSIS OF PRODUCTS A, B, AND C: TRADITIONAL VS. ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Gadget Co produces three products (A, B, and C) and is considering switching from traditional absorption costing to activity-based costing to improve profitability. The case involves calculating the full cost per unit for each product under both costing methods and analyzing how activity-based costing can enhance profitability.\"\"\",2\n158,\"\"\"ABC APPROACH\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity-Based Costing (ABC) approach allocates overhead costs based on multiple cost drivers, reflecting the actual effort and cost incurred in producing small batches. This approach results in a higher cost per unit for products like the Deluxe model, which should have a higher selling price to justify the higher costs incurred.\"\"\",2\n168,\"\"\"LABOR HOURS\"\"\",\"\"\"Labor hours refer to the total hours worked by employees directly involved in the production process. In traditional absorption costing, labor hours can be used as the single cost driver to allocate overhead costs.\"\"\",1\n2277,\"\"\"TRANSFER PRICE USING MACHINE HOURS\"\"\",\"\"\"Transfer price using machine hours is calculated by allocating overhead costs based on machine hours instead of labor hours. The formula involves dividing total overhead costs by total machine hours to get the overhead absorption rate, then adding this to the material and labor costs, and finally adding a 10% mark-up.\"\"\",1\n2229,\"\"\"STANDARD SELLING PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"Standard selling price is the budgeted price set for a product at the beginning of a period, based on market expectations.\"\"\",1\n2230,\"\"\"VARIABLE PRODUCTION COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Variable production costs are costs that vary directly with the level of production, such as materials and labor.\"\"\",1\n190,\"\"\"PERIOD COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Period costs are fixed costs that are treated as expenses in the period in which they are incurred, rather than being included in the unit cost, as in marginal costing.\"\"\",1\n163,\"\"\"OVERHEAD COST PER UNIT OF PRODUCT\"\"\",,1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n132,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity-based costing (ABC) is related to Absorption costing as both are costing methodologies, but ABC provides more detailed and accurate cost information by focusing on activities and cost drivers.\"\"\",34\n118,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"COST DRIVERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Cost drivers are used in ABC to allocate costs to activities.\"\"\",33\n110,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"TRADITIONAL ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity-based costing (ABC) is an alternative to Traditional absorption costing, providing a more accurate method of absorbing overhead costs into cost units.\"\"\",31\n122,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"EMA TECHNIQUES\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity-based costing (ABC) is an EMA technique.\"\"\",28\n117,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity-based costing (ABC) is a modern method used in management accounting to provide a more meaningful product cost by linking costs to the activities that drive them.\"\"\",27\n121,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"OVERHEAD COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Overhead costs are allocated to activities in ABC to determine the total cost of a product or service.\"\"\",26\n131,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"EVALUATING COSTING METHODS FOR ACCURATE PROCEDURE PRICING AT BECKLEY HILL HOSPITAL\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Evaluating Costing Methods for Accurate Procedure Pricing at Beckley Hill Hospital is related to Activity-based costing (ABC) as the hospital is considering implementing ABC for more accurate procedure pricing.\"\"\",26\n124,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"ABC IN MANUFACTURING QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"ABC in Manufacturing Quiz tests knowledge on the application and judgment required in activity-based costing in a manufacturing environment.\"\"\",25\n123,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"ABC IN SERVICE INDUSTRIES QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"ABC in Service Industries Quiz tests knowledge on the relevance and principles of activity-based costing in service industries.\"\"\",25\n120,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"ABSORPTION RATES\"\"\",\"\"\"Absorption rates are calculated in ABC to determine the overhead costs per unit of activity.\"\"\",25\n119,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"ACTIVITY COST POOLS\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity cost pools are groups of individual costs associated with a specific activity in ABC.\"\"\",25\n112,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"ACTIVITY OF ANAESTHETIST\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity of anaesthetist is an example of an activity used in ABC to calculate the cost of an operation.\"\"\",25\n114,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"ACTIVITY OF THE PHYSICIAN\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity of the physician is an example of an activity used in ABC to calculate the cost of an operation.\"\"\",25\n109,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"COST DRIVER\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity-based costing (ABC) uses cost drivers to attach activity costs to outputs.\"\"\",25\n111,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"PREPARING THE OPERATING THEATRE\"\"\",\"\"\"Preparing the operating theatre is an example of an activity used in ABC to calculate the cost of an operation.\"\"\",25\n113,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"ANAESTHETIC DRUGS\"\"\",\"\"\"Anaesthetic drugs is an example of an activity used in ABC to calculate the cost of an operation.\"\"\",25\n115,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"CONSUMABLE ITEMS DURING SURGERY\"\"\",\"\"\"Consumable items during surgery is an example of an activity used in ABC to calculate the cost of an operation.\"\"\",25\n116,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"OVERHEAD ACTIVITY\"\"\",\"\"\"Overhead activity is an example of an activity used in ABC to calculate the cost of an operation.\"\"\",25\n125,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: BUDGETED OVERHEAD COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on budgeted overhead costs uses the principles of activity-based costing (ABC) to calculate overhead costs per unit.\"\"\",25\n126,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: FIXED OVERHEAD COSTS IN ABC\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on fixed overhead costs in ABC uses the principles of activity-based costing (ABC) to calculate fixed overhead costs per unit.\"\"\",25\n127,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: ADVANTAGES OF ABC\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on the advantages of ABC involves identifying the benefits of using activity-based costing (ABC).\"\"\",25\n128,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION RANKING\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on throughput contribution ranking involves using the principles of activity-based costing (ABC) to rank products based on their throughput contribution.\"\"\",25\n129,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: OVERHEAD COST PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Quiz: Overhead Cost per Unit involves the application of Activity-based costing (ABC).\"\"\",25\n130,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: ABC AND TRADITIONAL COSTING SYSTEMS\"\"\",\"\"\"Quiz: ABC and Traditional Costing Systems compares Activity-based costing (ABC) with traditional costing methods.\"\"\",25\n233,\"\"\"FIXED PRODUCTION OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed production overheads are a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",17\n137,\"\"\"TRADITIONAL ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"The case compares traditional absorption costing with activity-based costing to determine which method improves profitability.\"\"\",16\n1316,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Environmental management accounting (EMA) uses activity-based costing (ABC) to manage environmental costs more effectively by identifying cost drivers and reducing their use without reducing output.\"\"\",16\n181,\"\"\"ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"SALES PRICE AND QUANTITY VARIANCES ANALYSIS FOR BLOCK CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Block Co uses an absorption costing system to allocate costs to its products.\"\"\",15\n1490,\"\"\"EVALUATING THE IMPACT OF ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING ON PRICING STRATEGIES AT BBB\"\"\",\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Evaluating the Impact of Activity-Based Costing on Pricing Strategies at BBB is related to Activity-based costing.\"\"\",15\n175,\"\"\"ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"